The problem is `IFormFile` buffers the entire request body into memory. Instead, read the raw request body stream directly to disk:

**1. Disable the default form body size limit and request buffering:**

```csharp
// Program.cs
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
{
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Read the boundary from the Content-Type header
    var boundary = request.GetMultipartBoundary();
    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(boundary))
        return Results.BadRequest("Missing multipart boundary");

    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    MultipartSection? section;

    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) != null)
    {
        if (ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(
                section.ContentDisposition, out var disposition)
            && disposition.IsFileDisposition())
        {
            var fileName = Path.GetRandomFileName(); // safe name
            var path = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName);

            await using var stream = File.Create(path);
            await section.Body.CopyToAsync(stream);       // streams to disk
        }
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete");
})
.DisableAntiforgery();
```

**2. Required usings:**

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities;   // MultipartReader
using Microsoft.Net.Http.Headers;          // ContentDispositionHeaderValue
```

**3. Key helper extension (if not already available):**

```csharp
// Already built-in via HttpRequestMultipartExtensions:
// request.GetMultipartBoundary()
// disposition.IsFileDisposition()
```

**Why this works:**

| Approach | Memory use | Mechanism |
|----------|-----------|-----------|
| `IFormFile` | Entire file in RAM | Buffered model binding |
| `MultipartReader` | ~80 KB buffer | Streams section-by-section |

**Additional tips:**

- Set `[RequestSizeLimit]` or `.WithMetadata(new RequestSizeLimitAttribute(...))` per-endpoint if you want different limits elsewhere.
- Consider writing to a temp file first, then renaming — protects against partial uploads.
- Add a `CancellationToken` parameter to handle client disconnects gracefully.
